1
00:00:02,697 --> 00:00:13,332
Foundation Course 2, Talk 9 The Sangha Sangha literally means comprising, so it comes to mean assembly and community.

2
00:00:14,614 --> 00:00:22,164
The Buddha was born into the Kshatriya, the warrior and ruling caste, and it seems his father, Suddhodana, was the chief of a council of rulers.

3
00:00:23,185 --> 00:00:25,088
This council was also called a Sangha.

4
00:00:26,370 --> 00:00:31,658
Before and during the Buddha's lifetime, the society was going through quite a fundamental change.

5
00:00:32,228 --> 00:00:36,893
It had been a pastoral society of wandering herdsmen centred on small market villages.

6
00:00:38,134 --> 00:00:45,402
But with the growth of agriculture and a more settled population, cities grew, and in them there came about a greater division of labour.

7
00:00:46,343 --> 00:00:57,594
So whereas in a pastoral society most could do most of the jobs, in a city-based agricultural society craftsmen developed who had specialised skills, such as wheelwrights and cobblers.

8
00:00:58,722 --> 00:01:05,572
Also with the cities, there grew a larger concentration of population and a more centralized system of government.

9
00:01:06,733 --> 00:01:10,718
Kings and courts began to develop, and this indeed was a profound political change.

10
00:01:11,599 --> 00:01:24,679
By the time the Buddha died, there were still some states who were ruled by a group of people, a sort of republic, but the area in which he lived, the great fertile plain north of the Ganges, had mostly come under the rule of autocratic kings.

11
00:01:26,515 --> 00:01:40,652
The importance of this little piece of history is to highlight the Buddha's own political leanings, which are not only developed in the discourses dealing with such matters, but are manifest most in how he organized the community of monastics, which he called the Sangha.

12
00:01:41,793 --> 00:01:51,004
In fact, before he passed away, the Buddha declared that his work was done since the Dharma had been taught and the four Sanghas established.

13
00:01:51,472 --> 00:02:03,290
These four sanghas, orders or communities, are the bhikkhu and bhikkhuni, that is, the monks and nuns, and the upasika and the upasika, the lay women and the lay men.

14
00:02:04,852 --> 00:02:10,562
He saw them as quite distinct orders, and more significantly, left no one in charge.

15
00:02:10,947 --> 00:02:17,977
In fact, when Ananda asks him who will rule them once he has passed away, the Buddha told him that the Dharma must be the guide.

16
00:02:18,698 --> 00:02:29,614
The Dharma here also included the rules of conduct he left, the Vinaya or discipline he left for the monastics, and the Sila, the morality rules he left for laypeople.

17
00:02:32,733 --> 00:02:40,763
So the Buddha himself did not follow the trend of his society in setting up an autocratic structure in the order, with a head, a lieutenant, sergeants and so on.

18
00:02:41,844 --> 00:02:51,556
He left it quite open, expecting the monastics and lay people to discuss openly any problem, for he was sure there was enough scriptural procedure for people to come to a correct decision.

19
00:02:52,959 --> 00:02:58,064
So far as the Buddha was concerned, he saw his followers as four distinct Sangha.

20
00:02:58,146 --> 00:03:05,317
each with their own way of life, non-governed by any person as such, but guided by the Dhamma, the teachings he had left.

21
00:03:07,280 --> 00:03:13,808
Legend has it that the first ever two disciples of the Buddha were in fact two laymen, the merchants Tapusa and Balika.

22
00:03:14,610 --> 00:03:19,516
But it was more probably the five disciples he delivered his first discourse to after his enlightenment.

23
00:03:20,397 --> 00:03:27,427
The same five in fact who had deserted him a little earlier, for they thought he had given up the quest upon eating a bowl of rice milk.

24
00:03:29,264 --> 00:03:37,933
From the first discourse, the turning of the wheel of the law, news seemed to have spread quickly about him, and ascetics approached him wanting to be his disciples.

25
00:03:39,074 --> 00:03:48,926
His reply was, Ehibikku, come Bikku, well explained is the Dharma, live the Brahmacharya, the holy life, for the complete ending of suffering.

26
00:03:50,649 --> 00:03:54,272
This was the formula of the first ordinations, the first makings of an order.

27
00:03:54,873 --> 00:03:56,115
It was as simple as that.

28
00:03:56,669 --> 00:04:02,018
However, when an originator cannot be present, followers often want to formalize things.

29
00:04:02,699 --> 00:04:10,772
And as the number of applicants grew and the order spread so that the distance became quite a problem, the Buddha allowed senior monks to ordain.

30
00:04:12,074 --> 00:04:18,987
In the end, a final ordination procedure was established and became known as the going for refuge in the triple gem.

31
00:04:19,588 --> 00:04:22,372
It is called the Upasampada ordination.

32
00:04:24,665 --> 00:04:31,572
The system established was that anyone who had been in the order for ten years or more could present someone to the order for admission.

33
00:04:32,192 --> 00:04:34,235
He is known as the postulant Upajaya.

34
00:04:35,377 --> 00:04:40,483
To ordain a monk it takes ten other monks, save in non-Buddhist countries where monks are rare.

35
00:04:41,043 --> 00:04:42,824
In such a case, five monks will do.

36
00:04:44,326 --> 00:04:47,870
At first the novice becomes a samanera, taking ten precepts.

37
00:04:48,307 --> 00:04:53,432
These are the usual five of the lay person, not to kill, not to take anything not freely given.

38
00:04:53,891 --> 00:05:02,100
The third, normally not to misuse the senses, here becomes a vow of chastity, of celibacy, a complete abstinence from all sexual conduct.

39
00:05:03,221 --> 00:05:07,646
Then there is not to steal and not to take any intoxicating drugs or drinks.

40
00:05:08,666 --> 00:05:17,975
The further five are not to eat after midday, not to wear perfumes or self-adornments like jewellery, not to go to entertainment such as dancing and films,

41
00:05:18,394 --> 00:05:23,901
not to sleep on high or luxurious beds, and finally, not to touch or handle money.

42
00:05:26,346 --> 00:05:32,053
Such precepts can also be taken by boys from the age of 8, and in fact Samanera means little ascetic.

43
00:05:33,314 --> 00:05:38,341
This is quite a common practice in Buddhist countries, and many stay to the age of 20 when they can ordain.

44
00:05:39,863 --> 00:05:47,894
Once these lower orders are taken, the novice can put on the monk's robes, and then, if he is of age and willing, he can take the higher ordination.

45
00:05:48,398 --> 00:05:56,428
This consists of answering a certain amount of questions to make sure there are no barriers to the monkhood, such as, does he have the permission of dependence?

46
00:05:57,230 --> 00:05:58,511
Does he have a serious illness?

47
00:05:58,971 --> 00:05:59,572
Is he in debt?

48
00:05:59,632 --> 00:06:00,053
And so on.

49
00:06:01,475 --> 00:06:11,689
Once the ordaining monks are satisfied, the postulant is then brought into the circle and told the rules of the Vinaya, the discipline, upon which, so long as he accepts them, he is received into the order.

50
00:06:12,901 --> 00:06:19,810
For the first five years he comes under a teacher, usually the person who introduced him to the order, the Upajaya, but not necessarily so.

51
00:06:20,952 --> 00:06:24,538
After five years he is known as a senior, and can teach if asked to do so.

52
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:30,166
After ten he is known as a Tera, or elder, and has the privilege of ordaining other monks.

53
00:06:31,509 --> 00:06:35,535
After twenty years he gains the title of Mahatera, or great elder.

54
00:06:36,435 --> 00:06:39,221
However, every country has its own way of addressing monks.

55
00:06:40,201 --> 00:06:42,165
Most people use the word Bhante,

56
00:06:42,584 --> 00:06:46,009
equivalent to venerable, when addressing a monk.

57
00:06:46,028 --> 00:06:59,627
But depending on the tradition, some call elders Ajahn, as in Thailand, which is a corruption of the word Acharya, meaning teacher, or if they are from Burma, they are addressed as Sayadaw, royal or noble teacher.

58
00:07:01,370 --> 00:07:06,456
Junior monks call senior monks Bhante, but senior monks call junior monks by their name.

59
00:07:09,420 --> 00:07:12,404
When it came to how to spend the day, the Buddha left no regimen,

60
00:07:13,026 --> 00:07:24,901
Although all monks have to eat before noon, and there are plenty of discourses advising monks how to spend their time wisely, in meditation and in learning the Dharma, the day is very much left up to the monk or monastery to organize.

61
00:07:26,062 --> 00:07:29,466
Monasteries have their own timetables, and some are quite highly organized.

62
00:07:30,487 --> 00:07:40,639
The Buddha himself advised the ardent monk to meditate in the first part of the night, sleep the second, and meditate again in the third part, in other words, to do with four hours sleep.

63
00:07:41,701 --> 00:07:42,882
But he doesn't make it a rule.

64
00:07:43,418 --> 00:07:48,824
Even in his own time, it seems, many could not summon up the energy needed for such strenuous practice.

65
00:07:49,586 --> 00:07:56,894
In fact, when it comes to the actual Vinaya, the discipline, the rules of the monastic life, they all grew up in a very organic way.

66
00:07:58,196 --> 00:08:05,144
The Buddha was asked early on to formulate rules and regulations, but he refused to do so, since the early monks had done no wrong.

67
00:08:06,266 --> 00:08:11,872
However, as they did do things that brought criticism either from other monks or from the lay people,

68
00:08:12,257 --> 00:08:16,863
The Buddha would consider the situation, and if he thought it appropriate, would declare a rule.

69
00:08:18,125 --> 00:08:25,634
For instance, the rule that says monks must eat before noon came about because lay people complained that monks were forever coming on alms round.

70
00:08:26,535 --> 00:08:38,669
The rules concerning the monk's behaviour with women, which strictly speaking is that he should not speak to a woman out of earshot, came about because of slander and indeed the odd dalliance of monks with women.

71
00:08:39,611 --> 00:08:44,898
In fact, when you look at the rules, you discover that a lot of them are about protecting the good name of the order.

72
00:08:46,139 --> 00:08:51,765
These days, some of the rules seem a little excessive, especially this relationship between monks and women.

73
00:08:52,447 --> 00:08:58,573
But you'll be surprised how the image of a sex-starved monk nipping over the monastery wall still persists in people's minds.

74
00:09:00,875 --> 00:09:08,504
A monk can't be too careful in this field, so don't be surprised if monks, especially from the Theravada tradition, don't even shake hands with women.

75
00:09:09,126 --> 00:09:14,975
Anyway, such a custom is not particularly an Eastern habit, where the greeting is to join hands and bow.

76
00:09:15,917 --> 00:09:32,099
Luckily, the Buddha's ministry lasted 45 years, during which all sorts of things happened, so that the final compilation of the Vinaya, the 227 rules, covers virtually all aspects of monastic life, and makes it very clear how the Buddha wanted his monks and nuns to behave.

77
00:09:34,923 --> 00:09:39,048
The rules are laid out in order of severity, and here we shall briefly mention a few.

78
00:09:40,091 --> 00:09:42,975
The most serious to break are known as the parajika, the defeats.

79
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:49,722
For if a monastic transgresses any of these four, they must leave the order and cannot rejoin again in this lifetime.

80
00:09:50,322 --> 00:10:00,514
They are to have any form of sexual intercourse whatsoever, to steal anything, to kill a human being, and to create a schism or split in the sangha.

81
00:10:01,735 --> 00:10:08,243
Then there follow thirteen rules for which the monk needs twenty other monks to reinstate him in the order, if they are broken.

82
00:10:08,965 --> 00:10:17,998
They include virtually any sexual behavior, groundlessly accusing another of having broken the parajikas, the defeats, and supporting a schism.

83
00:10:19,139 --> 00:10:21,864
There are then 30 rules entailing forfeiture.

84
00:10:22,565 --> 00:10:26,551
If a monk owns something he ought not to have, then it is simply taken away.

85
00:10:27,753 --> 00:10:30,836
There are 92 rules which are forgiven on the telling.

86
00:10:31,378 --> 00:10:36,205
They entail such things as abusive speech, lying, and even damage to plants.

87
00:10:37,754 --> 00:10:46,388
The rules also cover all the conduct appropriate between monastics and laypeople, among monastics themselves, and even how objects should be treated.

88
00:10:48,010 --> 00:10:52,158
There's a whole section of training rules that say how a monk should eat and robe.

89
00:10:53,179 --> 00:10:58,408
The final section lists the seven rules on how to settle disputes that arise within the order.

90
00:11:00,130 --> 00:11:03,035
I recommend a reading of the Patimokkha, as it is called.

91
00:11:03,421 --> 00:11:07,306
It will give you an insight into what a monk's life is all about.

92
00:11:08,006 --> 00:11:11,210
In short, it's about conduct, study and meditation.

93
00:11:11,831 --> 00:11:19,240
It's simply a refinement of the Noble Eightfold Path, sila, right conduct, samadhi, right meditation and paññā wisdom.

94
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:21,702
It's about the development of awareness.

95
00:11:22,244 --> 00:11:25,447
It's about behaving in a harmless, restrained, gentle way.

96
00:11:26,087 --> 00:11:30,052
It's about devoting one's life to self-introspection and learning.

97
00:11:30,033 --> 00:11:33,437
It's learning how to live at peace with oneself and with others.

98
00:11:36,462 --> 00:11:42,491
On a more mundane level, it's about achieving an absolute simplicity of lifestyle when it comes to material possessions.

99
00:11:43,514 --> 00:11:46,759
The Buddha wanted monks to have only those things that sustain life.

100
00:11:48,041 --> 00:11:50,024
Food, clothing, shelter and medicine.

101
00:11:51,446 --> 00:11:53,509
Just the bare necessities, nothing lavish.

102
00:11:53,870 --> 00:11:55,753
They're called the four requisites.

103
00:11:56,779 --> 00:12:17,197
The majority of monks still live at this level, and in a world increasingly swamped by consumerism and lost in the drive to achieve more and more personal possessions, such examples of simplicity of living will become more and more important in reminding people that there are other values, other ways of living, which may be more successful in terms of achieving peace and happiness.

104
00:12:18,460 --> 00:12:20,644
Not that everyone has to live on the breadline.

105
00:12:21,163 --> 00:12:23,668
It's more to do with attitudes to material wealth.

106
00:12:24,408 --> 00:12:31,178
It's that perspective which undermines attachment to sensual pleasure, whether expressed in goods or services.

107
00:12:32,221 --> 00:12:35,065
The perspective of what does it matter in the end.

108
00:12:36,988 --> 00:12:41,254
Propertylessness, on the personal level, is the hallmark of a monk.

109
00:12:42,155 --> 00:12:46,142
The monastery and all its contents belong to the sangha, the community.

110
00:12:46,577 --> 00:12:52,505
In the West, monasteries are usually trusts supported by laypeople, who are themselves the trustees.

111
00:12:53,888 --> 00:13:08,568
Although the rules specify only eight basic possessions a monk can have, such as his three robes and begging bowl, he is allowed other things, and these days you might find them owning the odd piece of modern gadgetry, such as an electric shaver and an alarm clock.

112
00:13:09,780 --> 00:13:17,832
This way of living is to bring our modern ideas of conservation down to a personal level, a simplicity of lifestyle.

113
00:13:20,456 --> 00:13:25,364
When it came to the community itself, the Buddha obviously wanted it to behave as a community of equals.

114
00:13:26,384 --> 00:13:34,977
His was indeed a revolutionary demand to ask anyone who joined the order to drop all pretense of caste, higher or lower, and simply join the end of the queue.

115
00:13:35,870 --> 00:13:40,636
No matter if an untouchable joined only the day before, the Brahmin followed him on alms round.

116
00:13:41,738 --> 00:13:48,346
What is more, in any decision-making within a given group of monks, all have the right to a say and to vote.

117
00:13:49,789 --> 00:13:52,693
Usually decisions made by the group are unanimous.

118
00:13:53,875 --> 00:14:03,008
What the Buddha obviously wanted was a real democracy in the sense that each individual was to be considered equal to anyone else and had a right to influence decisions.

119
00:14:04,321 --> 00:14:17,357
This in a society of a rigid caste system and a society turning more and more towards autocratic rule shows how clear the Buddha was in his ideas of what sort of basic rules lead to a peaceful and harmonious community.

120
00:14:19,379 --> 00:14:26,889
Even if a dispute grows within a certain group of monks that seems unresolvable they are allowed to part company and begin another sangha.

121
00:14:27,791 --> 00:14:32,336
A sangha here is any grouping of monks so long as there are four or over

122
00:14:33,768 --> 00:14:35,791
In this way, monks can agree to differ.

123
00:14:37,133 --> 00:14:46,644
At base, he destroyed the idea of personal wealth at the expense of others, and he demanded that everyone share responsibility by giving each equal power to vote.

124
00:14:47,767 --> 00:14:52,793
The fact that the Sangha has lasted over 2,500 years is testimony to his wisdom.

125
00:14:56,038 --> 00:14:59,842
Although the Bhikkhu Sangha, the order of monks, was quickly established...

126
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:08,547
The Bhikkhuni Sangha, the nuns, took a little longer to form, and came about through the unswerving efforts of Mahapajapati Gautami.

127
00:15:09,587 --> 00:15:17,076
She had been the Buddha's stepmother, his mother's sister, in fact, who died on giving birth to the Buddha.

128
00:15:17,096 --> 00:15:26,386
Once the Buddha's father Suddhodana died, Mahapajapati Gautami found herself free of family, so she decided to see if she could join the order as a monk.

129
00:15:27,548 --> 00:15:29,471
She went to ask the Buddha for ordination.

130
00:15:29,711 --> 00:15:31,153
He refused her three times.

131
00:15:32,134 --> 00:15:35,899
This seems to have been a ritual in those times to test the sincerity of the candidate.

132
00:15:37,020 --> 00:15:39,664
To refuse twice, but to accept the third time.

133
00:15:40,645 --> 00:15:45,932
Even now, Buddhists take the refuges three times, preserving this tradition of expressing one's determination.

134
00:15:47,294 --> 00:15:49,278
It was unusual to be refused a third time.

135
00:15:49,999 --> 00:15:53,082
However, Mahapajapati was not going to be disheartened.

136
00:15:53,451 --> 00:16:01,802
She and a small group of women with her donned the yellow robe and went again to seek the Buddha, who was over 150 miles away at Vesely.

137
00:16:02,725 --> 00:16:10,514
They arrived, exhausted and bedraggled, and again asked the Buddha three times, and again he refused to contemplate a bhikkhuni order.

138
00:16:13,318 --> 00:16:20,168
A lot of Westerners are now inclined to accuse the Buddha of sexism, but I think that's to look at it through 20th century eyes.

139
00:16:20,653 --> 00:16:35,157
To understand the Buddha's response, and to be fair, we need firstly to recognize just what a revolutionary he was for his times in many other ways, and secondly, what the status of women was in that society which made such an idea seem out of the question.

140
00:16:36,759 --> 00:16:42,328
He was a revolutionary, for instance, in his attitude to animal slaughter, especially the use of animals for sacrifice.

141
00:16:43,331 --> 00:16:47,336
It is said it was the Buddhists and their allies who eventually put an end to this useless ritual.

142
00:16:48,397 --> 00:16:52,522
He also condemned the caste system, which he destroyed in his own order.

143
00:16:54,043 --> 00:16:56,826
When it came to women, the prejudice against them went deeper still.

144
00:16:57,466 --> 00:17:01,431
One need only read the book of Manu to see that women were reduced to chattels.

145
00:17:02,331 --> 00:17:10,641
For instance, a man was able and indeed had to read the scriptures, the Vedas, and had to have sacrifices made in order to achieve spiritual advancement.

146
00:17:11,422 --> 00:17:14,105
A woman was unable and indeed forbidden to do this.

147
00:17:14,665 --> 00:17:16,647
She was told it was enough to be a good wife.

148
00:17:17,826 --> 00:17:32,307
Now there was not only this prejudice against women which firmly tied them to the household and which labelled them unable to have certain spiritual training or that it was needed or warranted there was also the conditions of the ascetic life itself as it was led in those days.

149
00:17:34,469 --> 00:17:39,375
In the Buddha's time monasteries as a place where monastics dwelt all the time were very rare indeed.

150
00:17:40,176 --> 00:17:47,547
Most ascetics anyway preferred to live the wanderer's life going into seclusion into the forest and searching out alms food in the villages and towns.

151
00:17:48,454 --> 00:17:54,523
Often they lived under trees and in caves, taking shelter in a monastery only during the four months of the monsoon.

152
00:17:56,026 --> 00:17:58,849
It was indeed a hard life, even by the standards of those times.

153
00:18:00,092 --> 00:18:05,058
What is more, the forests were the hideouts for bandits and criminals, not to talk of wild tigers.

154
00:18:06,141 --> 00:18:12,048
The idea of women wandering about even in groups would have seemed a wanton carelessness, asking for trouble.

155
00:18:12,838 --> 00:18:22,430
So the lack of precedence, the hardship of the life, remember also that Mahapajapati was a court lady, plus the dangers of the lifestyle, would have seemed great obstacles.

156
00:18:24,752 --> 00:18:33,002
However, the Buddha did finally agree, and it came about through the intervention of Ananda, his attendant and personal assistant during the last 20 years of his life.

157
00:18:33,983 --> 00:18:38,849
He asked the Buddha if it were possible for women to achieve the highest goal and become Arahats.

158
00:18:39,611 --> 00:18:41,292
The Buddha said, yes.

159
00:18:42,234 --> 00:18:48,124
If so, replied Ananda, shouldn't they be given the same opportunity as men to live the Brahmacharya, the holy life?

160
00:18:49,025 --> 00:18:52,088
The Buddha agreed, and so the Bhikkhuni order was established.

161
00:18:53,411 --> 00:19:02,684
However, he added eight extra rules to the Vinaya, the discipline, for the nuns, which established the relationship of the Bhikkhuni order to the Bhikkhu order.

162
00:19:03,405 --> 00:19:05,509
The Bhikkhuni are the junior order.

163
00:19:06,248 --> 00:19:08,951
Again, this need not be interpreted as sexist.

164
00:19:09,511 --> 00:19:20,323
In our society, when the three armed forces are together at a ceremony, the navy, being the most senior service, stands first, then the army, and then the air force in order of seniority.

165
00:19:22,605 --> 00:19:31,715
Unfortunately, the Bikuni order died out about a thousand years ago in the Theravadin tradition, though it is still very much alive in the Chinese Mahayana schools.

166
00:19:32,826 --> 00:19:39,234
These days there are many women and men who wish to reinstate the order, but to do so there needs to be a bikuni.

167
00:19:39,695 --> 00:19:40,217
Catch 22.

168
00:19:42,019 --> 00:19:46,825
What we do have today is women who have taken the eight precepts, which include the vow of celibacy.

169
00:19:47,506 --> 00:19:50,309
In Thailand they dress in white, in Burma pink.

170
00:19:51,050 --> 00:19:55,757
Here in Britain there are also nuns who have taken ten precepts of the lower orders of Samaneri.

171
00:19:56,277 --> 00:19:57,618
They are wearing brown robes.

172
00:19:59,201 --> 00:20:10,535
There is also a society, the Sangha Mita, called after the daughter of the Emperor Ashoka, the Arahant Sangha Mita, who went with her brother to Sri Lanka and converted the country to Buddhism.

173
00:20:11,536 --> 00:20:15,401
This organization is working for the re-establishment of a Bhikkhuni Sangha.

174
00:20:16,902 --> 00:20:22,929
Tibetan Buddhism also lacks the full order of Bhikkhuni, and the Dalai Lama has taken a great interest in this movement.

175
00:20:24,550 --> 00:20:27,775
It's difficult to know what will happen, but I myself am optimistic.

176
00:20:28,548 --> 00:20:42,355
Once there is a large enough caucus of women wanting the higher ordination, and the Buddhist community feels it just won't peter out, the question of Ananda will once more be invoked, and a formula will be established to reinstitute the Bhikkhuni order.

177
00:20:45,019 --> 00:20:48,125
So what are the duties and responsibilities of the monastics?

178
00:20:49,102 --> 00:20:59,051
Taking for granted that they must try to live the brahmacarya, the holy life, their two specific duties are to study the teachings, the dharma, and to practice the meditation, vipassana.

179
00:21:00,133 --> 00:21:03,276
To teach is only a duty in itself if asked to do so.

180
00:21:04,497 --> 00:21:08,701
Within a year of his first discourse, the Buddha sent monks off in all directions.

181
00:21:09,481 --> 00:21:16,087
Go forth, monks, for the benefit of the many, for the happiness of the many, out of compassion for the world.

182
00:21:17,721 --> 00:21:23,788
Because monks cannot teach unless they are asked, Buddhism has not developed into a proselytizing religion.

183
00:21:24,628 --> 00:21:27,612
People will come forward because of their interest and maturity.

184
00:21:28,051 --> 00:21:29,212
There's no need to convert.

185
00:21:31,134 --> 00:21:36,119
What about the other two orders, the lay women and the lay men, the Upasika and the Upasaka?

186
00:21:37,402 --> 00:21:44,808
The Buddha also left many guidelines, the five precepts and all sorts of advice concerning family relationships and social responsibilities.

187
00:21:45,650 --> 00:21:52,378
It also became a tradition for lay people to spend every half moon in the monastery and to take eight precepts for that day.

188
00:21:52,819 --> 00:21:56,023
This is still followed in the East.

189
00:21:56,044 --> 00:22:00,390
The relationship of the lay orders with the monastics is crucial to the well-being of Buddhism.

190
00:22:01,372 --> 00:22:07,259
The monastics depend upon the lay people for the four requisites, food, shelter, clothing and medicine.

191
00:22:08,442 --> 00:22:14,609
It is considered to be the lay person's responsibility to see that the physical needs of the monks and nuns are met.

192
00:22:15,501 --> 00:22:23,876
The lay people, in turn, look to the monastics for help concerning everyday problems of social or personal nature, but especially to spiritual guidance.

193
00:22:25,358 --> 00:22:27,923
They see the monks and nuns as the guardians of the Dharma.

194
00:22:28,846 --> 00:22:38,623
Although lay people hold monastics in veneration and show them high respect, they have also the duty to see to it that the Vinaya, the discipline, is preserved and well followed.

195
00:22:40,662 --> 00:22:47,272
There was a case, even in the Buddha's time, of a quarrel that arose between two monks and their followers at Kosambi.

196
00:22:48,515 --> 00:22:52,540
It was a dispute as to whether one of the monks had broken the Vinaya, the discipline, or not.

197
00:22:53,682 --> 00:22:59,311
The Buddha had come to sort out the quarrel, but they wouldn't listen to him, so he went off to live by himself in the forest.

198
00:23:00,493 --> 00:23:07,664
When the lay people heard about this, they refused to support the monks until they had gone to the Buddha, apologised and taken his advice.

199
00:23:08,336 --> 00:23:11,000
In this way they were forced to seek an end to their quarrelling.

200
00:23:12,163 --> 00:23:17,510
It is not unknown even these days for lay people to stop supporting monks who are not following the Vinaya.

201
00:23:20,074 --> 00:23:27,905
So here we see quite a clever interdependent interrelationship the Buddha contrived to establish between the monastics and the lay Sanghas.

202
00:23:29,208 --> 00:23:34,075
These days, however, the word Sangha is used to refer only to the monastics.

203
00:23:34,779 --> 00:23:42,510
But this use of the word must not be confused with its other meaning, the Ariya Sangha, the community of saints Buddhists take refuge in.

204
00:23:44,773 --> 00:23:48,960
Indeed, do not expect monks and nuns to be perfected enlightened ones.

205
00:23:49,780 --> 00:23:59,515
In the Buddha's time, there was a certain monk called Dabba the Malayan, who on becoming an Arahant and wondering how best to serve the Dharma, offered to take care of the monk's lodgings.

206
00:24:00,215 --> 00:24:02,880
The Buddha agreed it was a worthwhile thing to do,

207
00:24:03,518 --> 00:24:07,303
Dabba then set about dividing the monastic grounds into separate areas.

208
00:24:07,923 --> 00:24:13,412
In one part, he put all those who were interested in the discourses, so they could rehearse and discuss them.

209
00:24:14,313 --> 00:24:18,358
In another part, he put all those interested in the Vinaya, the discipline, for the same reason.

210
00:24:19,359 --> 00:24:22,545
He chose a quiet area for those who wished simply to meditate.

211
00:24:23,385 --> 00:24:29,694
And there was a special area designated for those who indulged in low talk and were athletic.

212
00:24:30,333 --> 00:24:35,298
So it would be a great mistake to see the Sangha as a ready-made supermarket of Arahats.

213
00:24:36,019 --> 00:24:40,263
On the other hand, it would be unjust to see them as a band of rogues.

214
00:24:40,284 --> 00:24:45,148
Monks and nuns are simply ordinary people who have decided to live in a particular way.

215
00:24:46,049 --> 00:24:47,832
Some do it with consummate dedication.

216
00:24:48,352 --> 00:24:50,434
Others, shall we say, bide their time.

217
00:24:52,797 --> 00:24:59,984
The Arya Sangha, the noble ones in whom Buddhists take refuge, are in fact those who have intuited Nibbana and have entered the paths.

218
00:25:00,775 --> 00:25:03,298
But this Sangha may belong to any of the orders.

219
00:25:04,259 --> 00:25:07,382
There is a very strong tradition of lay people achieving insight.

220
00:25:08,363 --> 00:25:15,871
Early this century there was an Arahant in Burma called Sunland Sayadaw, an illiterate farmer who achieved the third path before becoming a monk.

221
00:25:17,231 --> 00:25:25,019
The reason such people are taken as refuge is because of their knowledge, their experiential knowledge, of the third noble truth, the end of suffering.

222
00:25:26,142 --> 00:25:29,365
They are the past and living examples of the truth of the Dharma.

223
00:25:30,172 --> 00:25:36,059
Furthermore, because now they know for themselves, their faith in the Buddha Dharma is unshakable.

224
00:25:37,201 --> 00:25:41,087
By putting confidence in such people, Buddhists reinforce their own confidence.

225
00:25:42,470 --> 00:25:49,159
When you see a dentist's certificate, you have more confidence in the treatment and more confidence in yourself to undertake the treatment.

226
00:25:50,928 --> 00:25:59,057
Furthermore, their importance lies in the fact that they are the very purpose for which the Buddha worked so tirelessly for 45 years.

227
00:25:59,636 --> 00:26:04,001
For what is the point of the Dharma if it is not to get people to that enlightenment?

228
00:26:05,063 --> 00:26:12,611
What is the point of the four Sanghas if not to support those individuals who have the necessary perfections to achieve the highest goal?

229
00:26:13,432 --> 00:26:19,298
So, to take refuge in the noble Sangha, the saints, is to aspire to be one of their number.

230
00:26:22,585 --> 00:26:25,393
Well, I hope this talk has been interesting and helpful.

231
00:26:27,178 --> 00:26:28,803
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

232
00:26:29,645 --> 00:26:32,493
May all of you attain the Nirvanic peace within.

